node.text:
Japanese artist and designer Verdy (@verdy) always loved drawing characters. After years of doodling in notebooks, the iconic ‚ÄúVick‚Äù came to life. ‚úçüìí‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúI feel like we‚Äôve grown up together over many years,‚Äù says Verdy. ‚ÄúHaving the same personality as myself, he is always positive, takes on new challenges and is also pretty easygoing.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
The amount of time Verdy‚Äôs spent at home alone with his drawings last year gave him time to think about what‚Äôs important. ‚ÄúUp until now I thought I wanted to become an artist from Japan that gets to go out into the world. But now I want to be an artist that represents Asia.‚Äù üåè‚ú®‚Å£
‚Å£
If you‚Äôre needing some new year inspiration, #TakeABreak with Verdy (and his sidekick Vick) to see his work and passion in full force.

For artist Sipho Mabona (@siphomabona) beauty lies in the abstract. ‚ÄúFragments of crease patterns, which originally served as blueprints for origami sculptures, have become metaphors of what might have been,‚Äù he explains.‚Å£
‚Å£
Sipho‚Äôs process uses natural dyes and cotton fabric, and he finds that solitary moments of creation in his studio are some of the best ways to find calm and focus throughout his days.

Home. ‚ù§Ô∏è For artist Labo Maur√≠cio Lopes de Oliveira (@laboyoung), it‚Äôs the force behind his wearable pieces created from natural materials like leaves and coconut straws.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúMy work is how I enhance my Black, Marajoara and Ribeirinha culture,‚Äù says Labo, who lives in Bel√©m do Par√° in the Brazilian Amazon.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúIt started in my childhood, through games I played with my mom where we built a playful world ‚Äî creating games and toys from objects we found in our backyard, either foliage or seeds. These memories are with me even today and it‚Äôs where I still find inspiration for creation and experimentation.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
#ShareBlackStories

node.text:
‚ÄúWith my work what I hope to convey is that you can have fun and experiment,‚Äù says nail artist Natalie Pavloski (@nataliepnails). ‚Å£
‚ù§Ô∏èüíïüíú‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúBeing creative means so many things, you don‚Äôt have to solely focus on one thing and have it define you.‚Å£
‚Å£
Open yourself up to the possibilities and trust the process ‚Äî you can learn so much about yourself that way. It wasn‚Äôt intentional that hearts were recurring in my work but when I started painting them, it inspired me to do more.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
My primary focus has always been nail art, and playing around with makeup has been a fun and relatively new endeavor. Combining the two was experimental and is a really calming creative outlet.‚Äù ‚Å£
‚Å£
#ThisWeekOnInstagram‚Å£
‚Å£
Photos by @nataliepnails

Gardening = growth, literally and figuratively. No one knows that better than Marcus Bridgewater (@garden_marcus).‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúMy art and craft represents who I am in the way that I am attempting to approach all of life with kindness, patience and positivity ‚Äî regardless of what form of life it is or how prickly the plant may be.‚Äù üåµ‚Å£
‚Å£
This Black History Month, we continue to #ShareBlackStories and celebrate Black joy in all its glory. üñ§

‚ÄúI try to make big, bold statements in visual confusion and uncertainty, offset with colorful, sometimes friendly-looking forms,‚Äù says motion designer and 3D artist Ben Hughes (@rek0de).‚Å£
‚Å£
Ben‚Äôs 3D renderings place oversized forms ‚Äî including hearts, spheres and even giant creatures ‚Äî into urban environments, reshaping reality in unexpected and surprising ways.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúThe main theme in my work is around parallel realities and messing with juxtaposition, scale and physics. I‚Äôm fascinated by the quantum world. I‚Äôm equally fascinated by the character and stories contained in tower blocks and brutalist architecture. The two things together are such a fun contrast to work with.‚Å£
‚Å£
I think I‚Äôm trying to create light from darkness. Ordinarily, when one thinks about parallel worlds or realities, it can quickly become dystopian, but I don‚Äôt think it needs to be that way.‚Äù üíú‚Å£
‚Å£
#ThisWeekOnInstagram‚Å£
‚Å£
Video by @rek0de

node.text:
Artist Polina Osipova (@polinatammi) creates embroidery and jewelry inspired by folklore and symbols from her indigenous Turkic ancestry.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúMy art is an attempt to remember my childhood and to honor the Chuvash culture that I find mesmerizing,‚Äù says 22-year-old Polina, who‚Äôs from Cheboksary, the capital of the Chuvashia region of Russia.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúTo be born in a traditional Chuvash family means to be surrounded by arts and crafts on an everyday basis. As I learn more about our culture and traditions, I feel a deeper bond with my predecessors. Almost all of my recent projects are related to our people. I want them to be remembered. I am lucky to be able to talk to my grandmothers, hear the bedtime stories and superstitions they told me about when I was a child. From these experiences, ideas emerge.‚Å£
‚Å£
The heart symbol is widely used in our traditional embroidery and represents loyalty, unity, love and the Chuvash people themselves.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
#ThisWeekOnInstagram‚Å£
‚Å£
Video by @polinatammi

‚ÄúI was captivated by the rapid and intricate footwork, the quick steps and precise foot movement,‚Äù says 21-year-old Morgan Bullock (@morgvn.elizabeth), who discovered her passion for Irish dance at age 10. ‚ÄúIt was like nothing I‚Äôd ever seen before.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúIrish dance has taught me how to set goals for myself and work hard to achieve them. I love that it‚Äôs challenging, intense and there‚Äôs always more I can learn.‚Å£
‚Å£
When I dance, I feel complete bliss, any worries in the world that I have don‚Äôt matter for those few minutes.‚Å£
‚Å£
When people see me dance, I hope the message that is conveyed is that anyone and everyone, no matter who they are or where they come from, can enjoy the beautiful cultural art form that is Irish dance.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
